{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605964"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:06:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:06:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15884"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15884"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.32,0.37,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72048"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8575"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8581"},{"type":"tags","id":"10615"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20561"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72048"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe zona pellucida is a glycoprotein layer that surrounds and protects the developing embryo during early development. It prevents polyspermy during fertilisation and premature attachment to the fallopian tube epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes when the zona pellucida normally degenerates during early embryonic development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Day 5-6 post-fertilization","Day 3-4 post-fertilization","Day 7-8 post-fertilization","Day 9-10 post-fertilization","Day 11-12 post-fertilization"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona pellucida degenerates on day 5-6 post-fertilization\u003C/strong\u003E, a process known as \u0027hatching\u0027. This timing is crucial as it coincides with blastocyst formation and the window of endometrial receptivity for implantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 3-4 post-fertilization\u003C/strong\u003E - Too early; the embryo still requires protection during its transit through the fallopian tube\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 7-8 post-fertilization\u003C/strong\u003E - Too late for optimal implantation, which begins around day 6-7\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 9-10 post-fertilization\u003C/strong\u003E - Far too late for successful implantation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 11-12 post-fertilization\u003C/strong\u003E - Would prevent implantation entirely\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe loss of the zona pellucida allows the trophoblast cells of the blastocyst to make direct contact with the endometrium, which is essential for successful implantation. Prior to this, the zona pellucida provides crucial protection for the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The zona pellucida degenerates on day 5-6 post-fertilization, allowing for blastocyst hatching and subsequent implantation","Loss of the zona pellucida is essential for implantation as it allows direct contact between trophoblast cells and endometrium","The zona pellucida is a protective glycoprotein layer that prevents premature implantation and polyspermy"],"references":["Reid AT, 